<section>
  <h2>About</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>RefPin</strong> is a companion tool for
    <a href="https://beeref.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener">BeeRef</a>,
    the open-source reference image viewer. It connects BeeRef to the Pinterest API,
    letting artists and designers browse their Pinterest boards and selectively import
    reference images directly into their BeeRef canvas.
  </p>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>How It Works</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>A lightweight local Flask server handles Pinterest OAuth 2.0 authentication.</li>
    <li>You browse your Pinterest boards and pins inside a review dialog within BeeRef.</li>
    <li>Thumbnail previews are loaded asynchronously for quick browsing.</li>
    <li>You select the images you want, and they are inserted into your BeeRef scene.</li>
  </ol>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>Features</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Pinterest board and pin browsing via the official Pinterest API v5.</li>
    <li>Review dialog with async thumbnail loading, Select All/None, and selection count.</li>
    <li>Single-input dialog for streamlined authentication flow.</li>
    <li>Automatic session cleanup with TTL and max-session limits.</li>
    <li>All processing happens locally — no cloud, no tracking.</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>Architecture</h2>
  <p>The tool consists of two components:</p>

  <h3>BeeRef Plugin (Python/Qt)</h3>
  <p>
    Adds a "Pinterest → Import from Pinterest" menu action to BeeRef.
    Manages the review dialog UI where you browse, preview, and select images.
  </p>

  <h3>Helper Server (Flask)</h3>
  <p>
    A local HTTP server that handles the Pinterest OAuth flow and API requests.
    Runs on <code>localhost</code> only. Provides endpoints for session creation,
    approval, and image URL retrieval.
  </p>
</section>

